<H2>September 14, 2015 - Two New Baffle Designs</H2>


<p>


<hr>
<p>
  Comparison of the previous baffle with two new designs: one with a smaller radius than the first design which intersects the beam at 18 deg, and another shorter one that restores the previous intersection angle of 28 deg. 
<p>
The 18 deg baffle profile exhibits assymetric response about 0 deg, modest attenuation out to ~30 deg, and high response beyond that. The scaled down 28 deg baffle is more symmetric and performs significantly better all the way out to 60 deg. All profiles show reflections around ~80 deg.
<p>
<hr>

<H3>Fig. 1</H3>  
<p>
  Comparison of three unbaffled profiles and one very simple baffled profile as a control. Evidently changing from horizontal to vertical polarization has little effect on the unbaffled profile. All baffled trials were performed with vertical polarity. What looks like higher response at 50 deg is just one data point. The addition of a foam-only conical baffle has negligible to damaging effects - suggesting that our aluminum cylinder+rolled lip design is worth pursuing.
<p>Conical baffle <a href=http://caelum.uchicago.edu/~xhorn/photos/20150915_new_baffles/tn/IMG_0043.jpg.html>front,</a>
<a href=http://caelum.uchicago.edu/~xhorn/photos/20150915_new_baffles/tn/IMG_0044.jpg.html>side,</a>
& <a href=http://caelum.uchicago.edu/~xhorn/photos/20150915_new_baffles/tn/IMG_0045.jpg.html>top.</a>
<hr>
