<p>

 <H3>Fig. 2</H3>  
<p>
  Comparison of 4 baffled profiles. "in front" and "behind" refer to the difference between <a href=http://caelum.uchicago.edu/~xhorn/photos/20150915_new_baffles/tn/IMG_0021.jpg.html>trial #1,</a> where the back piece of an-73 was situated in front of the aperture, and <a href=http://caelum.uchicago.edu/~xhorn/photos/20150915_new_baffles/tn/IMG_0041.jpg.html>trial #2,</a> where we moved it behind the opening in order to reduce reflections from the thin face of the ID of the foam. While this lowered the response outside 45 deg, it seems to have done worse around 30 deg. 
<p>
  For the next trial we used a smaller diameter (same length) baffle such that it began to intersect the beam at 18 deg, in an attempt to increase the attenuation at smaller angles. We also added <a href=http://caelum.uchicago.edu/~xhorn/photos/20150915_new_baffles/tn/IMG_0058.jpg.html>a ring of aluminum sheet</a> sealed around the edges with aluminum tape behind the back piece of foam, in order to reduce any leakage from behind the baffle. We saw increased response at all angles greater than about 30 deg, and also distortion of the axial symmetry likely due to <a href=http://caelum.uchicago.edu/~xhorn/photos/20150915_new_baffles/tn/IMG_0057.jpg.html>overlapping foam</a> (see <a href="#fig4">fig. 4</a>).
<p>
  Intersecting the baffle so closely seems to divert power unpredictably - looking at the unbaffled beam we see that power is only ~10db from maximum at 18 deg, so introducing reflections this close is unwise. For the next trial we shrunk the length of the baffle so as to return to the original angle of 28 deg, with the added advantage of a more compact baffle. This trial yielded the best results so far - attenuation all the way to 60 degrees, reaching a maximum attenuation of 15dB at ~50 deg. Seeing as it doesn't matter in terms of radiant intensity from baffle reflections how large or small the baffle is (angle held equal), it makes sense to make it as compact as possible in order to minimize nonuniformities.
<p><a href=http://caelum.uchicago.edu/~xhorn/photos/20150915_new_baffles/tn/IMG_0069.jpg.html>Side view</a>
<p>
